Date: 14/1/1884
Source: Grey River Argus
Author:
Vol / Page: 2
Edition:
Quote: It will be recollected that for some time back those miners who had squatted on the railway reserve, being without any title to the ground, and liable to be ousted at any time Government might want it, endeavored to get Government to proclaim it ordinary Crown lands and throw it open for sale, so that they might purchase the freehold of the sections they are occupying.
Notes:

Date: 17/3/1891
Source: Grey River Argus
Author:
Vol / Page: 2
Edition:
Quote: From time to time one or two poor people squatted on the reserve, built comfortable little cottages for themselves, which are the means of keeping them off the benevolent aid fund; for if they did not squat there they would have to come to town, and consequently pay rent, which they would not be able to do.
